1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Fishing – A Sport of Patience, Sponsored by… Nothing Biting

2
00:00:05,100 --> 00:00:10,000
Fishing — it sounds simple: grab a rod, wait, reel in the fish.

3
00:00:10,100 --> 00:00:15,000
But in reality, it’s disguised meditation — stare at the water and your soul for 6 hours,

4
00:00:15,100 --> 00:00:17,500
just to pull up a chunk of pond weed.

5
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:22,000
They say fishing is elegant. Sure — if sweating in 40°C under anti-mosquito armor counts.

6
00:00:22,100 --> 00:00:27,000
Some go fishing like it's war: full gear, fancy rods, sunglasses, bait kits, and a foldable throne.

7
00:00:27,100 --> 00:00:32,000
But the only thing they reel in by sunset? A phone call: “You said 2 hours, it’s midnight!”

8
00:00:32,100 --> 00:00:37,000
Funny fails? Oh, there’s plenty.

9
00:00:37,100 --> 00:00:40,500
One guy fished for 3 hours and caught… a plastic sandal.

10
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:44,500
Another hooked a lost koi — someone’s pet that escaped from a garden pond.

11
00:00:44,600 --> 00:00:49,000
And one guy filmed his “epic catch,” but forgot to cut the part where he fell in.

12
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:53,000
His wife posted it with the caption: “My husband and his short-lived passions.”

13
00:00:53,100 --> 00:00:58,000
They say fishing brings peace. Sometimes… it also brings overdraft.

14
00:00:58,100 --> 00:01:02,000
Spend $200+ on pro gear — catch a fish the size of your pinky.

15
00:01:02,100 --> 00:01:06,000
Then comes that glorious moment — a fish bites!

16
00:01:06,100 --> 00:01:10,000
Heart racing, hands trembling, everyone holding their breath...

17
00:01:10,100 --> 00:01:13,000
And you pull up a fish smaller than your snack.

18
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:17,000
But it’s not about eating — it’s about telling stories.

19
00:01:17,100 --> 00:01:20,000
And in those stories, the fish is always twice as big.

20
00:01:20,100 --> 00:01:25,000
Fishing isn’t just a hobby — it’s patience, hope, and self-reassurance:

21
00:01:25,100 --> 00:01:28,000
“It’s okay. Next time, I’ll get lucky.”